orcement of dominant discourses in multiple social arenas; the aligning of marginalized group identities with dominant institutional practices; and the selective promotion of the interests of specific, non-elite groups.This is the first book to argue that violence is both a negative, coercive power and a positive, productive one that helps produce not only social order but also consent, discipline, discourse, identity, subjectivity, and embodied knowledge, among other things. The Violent Underpinnings of American Life is an audacious work that argues violence is absolutely central to social life in America, and that Americans cannot effectively fight against the inequalities that surround them without accepting this reality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSocial controlzUnited States. 0aViolencezUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aAmerican ideals.  aAmerican social hierarchy.  aBlack Lives Matter.  aBourdieu.  aFoucault.  aGramsci.  aPolitical violence against African-Americans.  aWhites.  aamerican history.  abooks about violence in America.  abooks about violence.  aconsent.  adiscipline.  aelite power.  aembodied knowledge.  agun violence.  aidentity.  amarginalized groups.  aneoliberal.  apatriarchy.  apolice violence.  arape.  asexual harassment.  asexual violence.  asocial divisions.  asocial life.  asocial order.  asocial science.  asubjectivity.  aviolence in America.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishz9783111319254